 "noopener" title="https://www.trumba.com/i/DgCLCd2AytQoPArk0HKz52kP.jpg"
 >www.trumba.com&#8230\;</a>
DTSTAMP:20260309T092238Z
DESCRIPTION:<p>What roles do artists play in civil society? What do arti
 sts think about when they think about making things in public? Is art a 
 basic need? Join us in conversation with Nakisa Dehpanah\, Titus Ross\, 
 and Imani Sims&#8212\;three artists pushing towards a future rooted in c
 ollaboration\, resilience\, and transformation.<br><br>Each artist is pa
 rt of the Seattle Office of Arts &amp\; Culture&#8217\;s collective imag
 ining\, &#8220\;We Still Dream a Future&#8221\;. This series features mo
 re than thirty artists and artist groups performing\, dancing\, installi
 ng\, learning\, organizing\, and exhibiting around Downtown\, the C-ID\,
  Pioneer Square\, Stadium District\, Union and King Street Stations this
  year.<br><br>The conversation will be hosted by Matthew Offenbacher\, S
 eattle artist and advisor for ARTS at King Street Station.<br><br>This p
 rogram is supported by the City of Seattle Office of Arts &amp\; Culture
  and is part of the commUNITY series\, a selection of free public progra
 ms that center connection\, career development\, and the co-creation of 
 art curated by&#160\;ARTS at King Street Station Advisors.&#160\;</p><hr
 ><p><strong>About the artists</strong>:<br><strong>Nakisa Dehpanah</stro
 ng> explores the relationship between the body and imposed structures&#8
 212\;political\, spatial\, and cultural&#8212\;through sculptural instal
 lation and video. Using textile-based forms and movement documentation\,
  the work examines how displacement shapes memory and belonging\, tracin
 g the body&#39\;s capacity to adapt\, resist\, and transform across diff
 erent environments and lived experiences.<br><br><strong>Titus Ross</str
 ong> is a Seattle-based fashion designer\, creative director\, and found
 er of thirty+. A self-taught artist\, he began creating with whatever re
 sources he could find\, shaping a vision that now reaches audiences acro
 ss the U.S.\, the UK\, China\, France\, and Africa. His work transforms 
 discarded materials into garments that carry stories of resilience\, ide
 ntity\, and community. Runways for Ross are never just about clothes&#82
 12\;they&#8217\;re living spaces where music\, performance\, and fashion
  collide to spark dialogue and connection. Projects like Grassroots and 
 PNW Fashion Week: Sustainability Matters reflect his belief that fashion
  can be both sustainable and deeply inclusive. For Ross\, fashion is mor
 e than clothes&#8212\;it&#8217\;s a movement\, a safe space\, and a chan
 ce to reimagine what we leave behind and what we carry forward.<br><br><
 strong>Imani Sims</strong> is an alchemist and author from Seattle\, WA.
  Wonder is Imani&#8217\;s specialty and drawing inspiration from the cos
 mos to integrate art\, ritual\, and the Black aesthetic into experiences
  tailored for QTBIPOC communities and allies. With a background spanning
  over three decades in performance &amp\; literature\, they&#8217\;ve de
 dicated themselves to fostering spaces where imagination thrives. Their 
 shelves overflow with books delving into Afrofuturist realms\, and their
  tarot deck\, The Deck of N0NE\, embodies their deep connection to the g
 enre. Imani&#8217\;s work is a world within a world. Find Imani on Insta
 gram @bookthirtythree &amp\; <a href="https://protect2.fireeye.com/v1/ur
 l?k=31323334-50bba2bf-31321b84-4544474f5631-e252c97ba796ec54&amp\;q=1&am
 p\;e=a71d4ed8-45de-496b-a0d7-c1e6d7a2cb28&amp\;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwwww.thede
 ckofnone.com%2F" target="_blank" rel="noopener">wwww.thedeckofnone.com</
 a><br><br><strong>About the host:<br>Matthew Offenbacher</strong> is a l
 ong-time Seattle artist and community organizer. His work has been calle
 d &#8220\;freakishly egoless\,&#8221\; vulnerable\, funny and queer. Ove
 r the past several years\, he has made an installation of protection cha
 rms in I-5 Colonnade Park\, a painting installation with four dancers\, 
 a musician and a bystander intervention trainer\, and a giant walk-in fi
 sh belly made of PVC pipe that was also a percussion instrument and temp
 orary performance space.<br><br><strong>About the series</strong>:<br>Th
 e <a href="https://artbeat.seattle.gov/2025/10/22/community-fall-lineup/
 " target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>commUNITY series</strong></a> i
 s a selection of free public programs that center connection\, career de
 velopment\, and the co-creation of art. Curated by&#160\;<a href="https:
 //www.seattle.gov/arts/programs/arts-at-king-street-station#about" targe
 t="_blank" rel="noopener">ARTS at King Street Station Advisors</a>\, thi
 s series brings together their visions and talents to build community\, 
 engage attendees in powerful arts practices\, and offer free career deve
 lopment and skill-building for all ages. This series features workshops 
 by Ashanti Davis\, Alicia Mullikin\, Shaudi Vahdat\, Scott Oshima\, and 
 Marie Kidhe.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
