DESCRIPTION:<p><strong>Join ARTS on the&#160\;King Street Station plaza 
 for <em>Multilingual Indigenous Music</em>&#160\;by Khu.&#233\;ex&#39\;.
 </strong><br><br>Seattle based multi-tribe band Khu.&#233\;ex&#8217\; (k
 oo-EEK) uses their Tlingit\, Haida\, Blackfeet music and languages as in
 spiration. This collective of artists creates a unique sound\, which lay
 s a foundation for traditional vocals to be interspersed with spoken wor
 d and storytelling.</p><p>The band explores Jazz/Gospel and Funk/Rock wi
 th an improvisational style. The fusion of these styles with spoken word
  in English\, Tlingit\, Haida languages is unique. They strive&#160\;to 
 preserve these native languages though their&#160\;music. This cross-fer
 tilization results in a new sound. Performance art\, using traditional m
 asks and regalia\, accent the dynamic live performances.</p><p><em>We St
 ill Dream a Future</em>&#160\;is&#160\;a series of free public art activ
 ations\, installations\, exhibitions\, performances\, and learning exper
 iences designed to help us dream\, learn\, and grow\, taking place&#160
 \;throughout the Downtown core.</p><hr><p>Gallery hours are Wed. &#8211\;
  Sat. 11 a.m. &#8211\; 5 p.m.\; First Thursdays 11 a.m. &#8211\; 8:00 p.
 m.<br><br><strong><a href="https://www.khueex.com/" target="_blank" rel=
 "noopener">Khu.&#233\;ex&#39\;</a>&#160\;Members</strong><br>Preston Sin
 gletary (bass\, vocals)\, Gene Tagaban (vocals/flute/hand drum)\, Captai
 n Raab (guitar/vocals)\, Denny Stern (percussion)\, Tim Kennedy (keyboar
 ds)\, Ed Littlefield (drums/vocals)\, Sondra Segundo (vocals/hand drum)
 \, Arias Hoyle (vocals) and Jason Cressey (trombone).</p><p>Members of th
 e band bring light to aspects and cultural perspectives of Indigenous pe
 ople. Performances reach out to a wide demographic from very young to ol
 der audiences. The live performances are uplifting and include dancing w
 ith traditional regalia. The backgrounds of this collective of band memb
 ers include engaging with communities in various ways\, both close to ho
 me in the Pacific Northwest and globally.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
