DESCRIPTION:<p><strong>Join ARTS at King Street Station for <em>Setting 
 of the Daybreak Star</em></strong><strong>\,&#160\;a series of plaza con
 certs</strong> <strong> hosted by United Indians of All Tribes Foundatio
 n\, Daybreak Star Radio Network</strong><strong>. July features a perfor
 mance by Ribbon Skirt!&#160\;</strong><br><br>This series of events on t
 he King Street Station Plaza creates an urban sanctuary where participan
 ts can gather in celebration as the day transitions to evening. The prog
 rams&#160\;highlight Indigenous performers\, creating an accessible entr
 y point for communities to engage with Native music and&#160\;cultural t
 raditions.<br><br>Join us for four sessions in 2026\, on the second Thur
 sdays of June through September.<br><br><em>We Still Dream a Future</em>
 &#160\;is&#160\;a series of free public art activations\, installations
 \, exhibitions\, performances\, and learning experiences designed to help
  us dream\, learn\, and grow\, taking place&#160\;throughout the Downtow
 n core.<br><br><strong>SERIES SCHEDULE (2nd Thursdays)</strong>:</p><ul>
  <li>June 11&#160\;&#8212\; Supaman	</li><li>July 9&#160\;&#8212\; Ribbo
 n Skirt	</li><li>August 13&#160\;&#8212\; The Neighborhood Kids	</li><li
 >September 10&#160\;&#8212\; TBA!</li></ul><hr><p>Gallery hours are Wed.
  &#8211\; Sat. 11 a.m. &#8211\; 5 p.m.\; First Thursdays 11 a.m. &#8211
 \; 8:00 p.m.<br><br><strong>Artist bio:<br>Ribbon Skirt</strong> is a Mon
 treal-based band led by Anishinaabe musician Tashiina Buswa and guitaris
 t Billy Riley. Their sound is raw and enveloping\, channeling angular gu
 itars\, driving rhythms\, and lyrical threads that explore memory\, love
 \, grief\, and Buswa&#8217\;s relationship to her Indigenous heritage. T
 heir debut album\, <em>Bite Down</em> (Mint Records\, April 2025)\, was 
 met with critical acclaim and quickly established Ribbon Skirt as one of
  the most compelling new voices in indie music - earning Stereogum&#8217
 \;s Album of the Week and a shortlist nomination for the 2025 Polaris Mu
 sic Prize.<br><br><strong>Organizer bio:</strong><br><a href="https://un
 itedindians.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Daybreak Star R
 adio</strong></a> is<strong>&#160\;</strong>a Native American radio stat
 ion with a sacred mission to Indigenize the airwaves. Their&#160\;team i
 s 100% Native American\, with every staff member actively engaged in the
 ir tribal communities. Their managers bring diverse creative backgrounds
  as artists\, theatre workers\, and musicians\, infusing programming wit
 h authentic cultural perspectives. The station serves as a vital cultura
 l hub for Native American\, First Nations\, and Pacific Islander communi
 ties\,&#160\;showcasing Indigenous artists and voices that are typically
  underrepresented in mainstream media. This commitment stems from their 
 deep connections to our heritage and ancestral knowledge systems.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
