DESCRIPTION:<p><strong>Join ARTS at King Street Station for <em>Setting 
 of the Daybreak Star</em></strong><strong>\,&#160\;a series of plaza con
 certs</strong> <strong> hosted by United Indians of All Tribes Foundatio
 n\, Daybreak Star Radio Network</strong><strong>. August features a perf
 ormance by The Neighborhood Kids!</strong><br><br>This series of events 
 on the King Street Station Plaza creates an urban sanctuary where partic
 ipants can gather in celebration as the day transitions to evening. The 
 programs&#160\;highlight Indigenous performers\, creating an accessible 
 entry point for communities to engage with Native music and&#160\;cultur
 al traditions.<br><br>Join us for four sessions in 2026\, on the second 
 Thursdays of June through September.<br><br>We Still Dream a Future&#160
 \;is&#160\;a series of free public art activations\, installations\, exh
 ibitions\, performances\, and learning experiences designed to help us d
 ream\, learn\, and grow\, taking place&#160\;throughout the Downtown cor
 e.<br><br><strong>SERIES SCHEDULE (2nd Thursdays):</strong></p><ul> <li>
 June 11&#160\;&#8212\; Supaman	</li><li>July 9&#160\;&#8212\; Ribbon Ski
 rt	</li><li>August 13&#160\;&#8212\;The Neighborhood Kids	</li><li>Septe
 mber 10&#160\;&#8212\; TBA!</li></ul><hr><p>Gallery hours are Wed. &#821
 1\; Sat. 11 a.m. &#8211\; 5 p.m.\; First Thursdays 11 a.m. &#8211\; 8:00
  p.m.<br><br><strong>Artist bio:<br>The Neighborhood Kids</strong> are a
  fast-emerging conscious hip-hop band comprised of uniquely talented ind
 ividuals: Verde\, Amon the MC\, Niko Rosy\, Gatoz Locoz\, and DJ JG. Tog
 ether\, they use their music to promote awareness for child abuse\, wome
 n&#8217\;s rights\, police reform\, drug abuse\, immigration laws\, and 
 other marginalized groups.<br><br><strong>Organizer bio:</strong><br><a 
 href="https://unitedindians.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong
 >Daybreak Star Radio</strong></a> is<strong>&#160\;</strong>a Native Ame
 rican radio station with a sacred mission to Indigenize the airwaves. Th
 eir&#160\;team is 100% Native American\, with every staff member activel
 y engaged in their tribal communities. Their managers bring diverse crea
 tive backgrounds as artists\, theatre workers\, and musicians\, infusing
  programming with authentic cultural perspectives. The station serves as
  a vital cultural hub for Native American\, First Nations\, and Pacific 
 Islander communities\,&#160\;showcasing Indigenous artists and voices th
 at are typically underrepresented in mainstream media. This commitment s
 tems from their deep connections to our heritage and ancestral knowledge
  systems.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
