DTSTAMP:20260223T101119Z
DESCRIPTION:<p><strong>Join ARTS at King Street Station for <em>Buwaya B
 aby</em>\,</strong> <strong>an interdisciplinary fashion show and instal
 lation by Heidi Grace Acu&#241\;a</strong><strong>.</strong><br><br>Heid
 i Grace Acu&#241\;a&#39\;s artist residency at ARTS at King Street Stati
 on culminates in an interdisciplinary fashion show exploring native trad
 itions\, spirituality\, and folklore in the Philippines and in the US di
 aspora.<br><br><em>We Still Dream a Future</em>&#160\;is&#160\;a series 
 of free public art activations\, installations\, exhibitions\, performan
 ces\, and learning experiences designed to help us dream\, learn\, and g
 row\, taking place&#160\;throughout the Downtown core.</p><hr><p>Gallery
  hours are Wed. &#8211\; Sat. 11 a.m. &#8211\; 5 p.m.\; First Thursdays 
 11 a.m. &#8211\; 8:00 p.m.<br><br><strong>Artist bio:</strong><br><stron
 g><a href="https://www.heidigraceacuna.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopen
 er">Heidi Grace Acu&#241\;a</a>&#160\;</strong>(HGA/they/she) is an arti
 st who &#8220\;creates to live&#8221\;. Born in Federal Way\, Washington
  to immigrant Filipino parents\, and raised on O&#8216\;ahu since one ye
 ar old\, Heidi felt disconnected to a true sense of home and belonging. 
 Now\, Heidi makes art that finds the beauty in the multiplicities\, impe
 rfections\, and expansiveness of identity\, culture\, gender\, and home.
  Heidi&#8217\;s interdisciplinary work in ceramic sculpture\, textiles\,
  and printmaking is inspired by the diverse tropical colors of her islan
 d homes\, living in diaspora\, and the need for connection.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
